<P>
TOP STORIES:
</P>
<P>
Rice says U.S. will not "abandon the innocent Palestinians in
Gaza"
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice says the
U.S. "will not abandon the innocent Palestinians in Gaza,"
shortly after Israel declared the territory to be an enemy entity
and said it would cut off power and fuel supplies to it. At the
same time, Rice said Gaza, ruled by the Islamic militant Hamas
group, "is a hostile entity to us as well."  Developing.
</P>
<P>
World stock markets rise after U.S. Fed cuts interest rates
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- World stock markets rally in the wake of Wall Street's
overnight surge spurred by the U.S. Federal Reserve's larger-
than-expected interest rate cut, which was aimed at keeping
problems in the mortgage market from causing a recession in the
U.S. economy, a key export market for many Asian and European
companies.  MARKETS. Developing. By Toby Anderson.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- FRANKFURT, Germany -- The euro keeps soaring against the U.S.
dollar, reaching its all-time high in the aftermath of a half-
percent rate cut by the U.S. central bank. Developing. By Matt
Moore.
</P>
<P>
-- PRICES. Oil prices rise above the previous session's record
close, lifted by expectations the U.S. interest rate cut will
accelerate growth and increase demand for already tight crude and
gasoline supplies. Developing. By Pablo Gorondi.
</P>
<P>
-- ANALYSIS. WASHINGTON -- Ben Bernanke is finding that the
nation's financial markets can be tough graders. He also is
demonstrating that he can be a quick learner. Moved.
</P>
<P>
Top former Khmer Rouge leader charged with crimes against
humanity
</P>
<P>
PAILIN, Cambodia -- Nuon Chea, the top surviving leader of
Cambodia's notorious Khmer Rouge, whose radical policies were
responsible for the deaths of an estimated 1.7 million people, is
charged with crimes against humanity and war crimes.  ROUGE.
Developing. By Ker Munthit. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
MIDDLE EAST:
</P>
<P>
Iraqi prime minister disputes Blackwater USA's version of weekend
shooting
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq's prime minister disputes Blackwater USA's
version of a weekend shooting that left at least 11 people dead
and declares he will not tolerate "the killing of our citizens in
cold blood."  Developing. By Qassim Abdul-Zahra. AP Photos
BAG101-102.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- WASHINGTON -- Iraq's temporary ban of Blackwater USA reveals a
growing web of rules governing weapons-bearing private
contractors but few signs U.S. agencies are aggressively
enforcing them. Moved. By Richard Lardner. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
-- REFUGEES. WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration will name two
senior officials to straighten out its handling of Iraqi refugees
in response to numerous complaints that Washington is failing to
meet pledges to admit thousands who have fled the country. Moved.
By Eileen Sullivan and Matthew Lee.
</P>
<P>
Iran set to retaliate in case of attack by Israel, says air force
chief
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN, Iran -- The deputy commander of Iran's air force says
that plans have been drawn up to bomb Israel if the Jewish state
attacks Iran, according to the semi-official Fars news agency.
Developing.
</P>
<P>
EUROPE
</P>
<P>
Turkey's PM says ban on headscarf should be removed
</P>
<P>
ISTANBUL, Turkey -- A ban on women wearing Islamic headscarves in
Turkish universities should be lifted, the country's prime
minister says, signaling a significant change in his stance on
the contentious issue.  Moved. By C. Onur Ant.
</P>
<P>
Envoys meet in London on Kosovo's future
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Kosovo's ethnic Albanian leaders join talks on the
future of the disputed province with envoys from the United
States, European Union and Russia amid concerns that patience is
at breaking point.  Developing. By Danica Kirka. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Giuliani visits Britain, meets with political leaders, Margaret
Thatcher
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Rudy Giuliani meets Britain's political leaders, the
latest Republican presidential candidate to meet the country's
new political guard and Margaret Thatcher, an icon among American
conservatives.  Developing; roundtable at 1645GMT. By Paisley
Dodds. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Crackdown on French delicacy: a songbird served sizzling and
swallowed whole
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- On the world's list of weird foods, ortolan -- a bite-
size songbird roasted and gulped down whole -- can claim a place
of distinction. But the ortolan is protected by French law and
the government is out to get poachers hunting the coveted fowl.
SONGBIRDS. By Jenny Barchfield. AP Photo.
</P>
<P>
AFRICA:
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu radio station shuts down after receiving threats,
director says
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU, Somalia -- An influential Somali radio station goes
off the air after two government soldiers threatened to pound the
building with "machine guns and anti-aircraft missiles," the
radio station's director said.  Moved. By Mohamed Olad Hassan.
</P>
<P>
Disease, hunger, fish swimming through the streets -- Africa
copes with floods
</P>
<P>
SOROTI, Uganda -- The worst floods in decades are devastating
Africans across the continent, sending residents to higher ground
and sparking fears of food crises and outbreaks of disease.
FLOODS. Developing. By Katy Pownall. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
ASIA:
</P>
<P>
Wipha weakens after sweeping eastern China where 2 million moved
from coastal areas
</P>
<P>
SHANGHAI, China -- Typhoon Wipha weakens as it sweeps through
eastern China, bringing torrential rains that flooded streets and
disrupted air traffic but caused little damage in China's
financial center of Shanghai.  Developing. By Elaine Kurtenbach.
AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Buddhist monks press peaceful protests in Myanmar amid tight
security
</P>
<P>
YANGON, Myanmar -- Buddhist monks staging anti-government
protests in Myanmar push past closed gates to occupy a pagoda in
downtown Yangon, witnesses say.  Developing. AP Photo.
</P>
<P>
US-led coalition accuses Taliban of using children as human
shields
</P>
<P>
KABUL, Afghanistan -- The U.S.-led coalition accuses the Taliban
of using children as human shields during a battle in southern
Afghanistan, while NATO says it is investigating a shipment of
weapons intercepted near the border with Iran.  Developing. By
Rahim Faiez. AP Photo HMD102.
</P>
<P>
NORTH AMERICA:
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors file charges against O.J. Simpson, including
kidnapping
</P>
<P>
LAS VEGAS -- Prosecutors filed formal charges against O.J.
Simpson, alleging the fallen football star committed 10 felonies,
including kidnapping, in the armed robbery of sports memorabilia
collectors in a casino-hotel room.  THEFT-SIMPSON. Moved. By
Kathleen Hennessey. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Spector judge considers letting jurors choose lesser charge to
break impasse
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- The judge in the murder trial of music legend Phil
Spector says he is considering giving jurors the option of
finding the record producer guilty of a lesser charge than second
degree murder after the they reported a 7-5 impasse following
seven days of deliberations.  SPECTOR. Developing. By Linda
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
LATIN AMERICA:
</P>
<P>
Chiquita's US court settlement over paramilitary payments sparks
outrage in Colombia
</P>
<P>
BOGOTA, Colombia -- Colombia's interior minister slams a U.S.
judge's approval of a US$25 million (euro18 million) fine for
Chiquita Brands International Inc., saying the company was able
to get off cheap for making payments to a militia responsible for
killing thousands of Colombians.  FINE. Moved. By Joshua Goodman.
</P>
<P>
Cuba claims US embargo has cost island more than US$89 billion to
date
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Washington's 45-year-old embargo has cost Cuba more
than US$89 billion (euro64 billion) to date, wreaking havoc on
everything from primary education to pest control and nearly all
other facets of island life, the foreign minister says.  EMBARGO.
Moved. By Will Weissert. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Argentines march to demand return of missing Dirty War witness
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, Argentina -- Thousands of protesters march through
Buenos Aires demanding authorities solve the case of Jorge Julio
Lopez, who disappeared a year ago after testifying in a criminal
trial stemming from dictatorship-era abuses.  MAN. Moved. By Bill
Cormier. AP Photos XNP 101-103.
</P>
<P>
BUSINESS &amp; FINANCE:
</P>
<P>
Bank of England plans to inject funds in money market, marking
change in policy
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Bank of England announces that it will inject funds
into the longer-term money market, marking a major reversal in
its policy on bailing out struggling banks and fuelling
accusations that British authorities have mishandled the credit
crisis.  OF ENGLAND. Developing. By Jane Wardell.
</P>
<P>
RBS-led consortium favored as ABN Amro shareholders discuss rival
takeover bids
</P>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, Netherlands -- A consortium of banks led by Royal Bank
of Scotland PLC has emerged as the clear favorite to win ABN Amro
as shareholders of the prepared to meet and discuss rival bids
for the Dutch bank.  AMRO-TAKEOVER BATTLE. Upcoming. By Toby
Sterling.
</P>
<P>
Big drop in energy costs sends consumer prices down for the first
time in 10 months
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. consumer prices in August fell for the first
time in 10 months, as another big drop in energy costs offset
higher food prices.  Moved. By Martin Crutsinger.
</P>
